Information about Dataset¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rikdifos/credit-card-approval-prediction/data

Don't ask me where this data come from, the answer is I don't know!

Each observation represents a client.

Some variables:

  • CODE_GENDER: gender,
  • FLAG_OWN_CAR: whether client owns a car,
  • FLAG_OWN_CAR: whether client owns a property,
  • CNT_CHILDREN: client's number of children,
  • AMT_INCOME_TOTAL: client's annual income,
  • NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE: client's educational level,
  • NAME_FAMILY_STATUS: client's marital status,
  • NAME_HOUSING_TYPE: client's manner of living,
  • DAYS_BIRTH: birth_days,
  • and more.

I'm interested in this dataset because the variables looks rather interesting and the number of observations is high. Furthermore, I need my credit score to increase.

Finding Things to Explore¶

There are some questions I can try to answer:

  1. What is the average total income (AMT_INCOME_TOTAL) of each education type (NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE)?
  2. Is there a relationship between the number of family members (CNT_FAM_MEMBERS) and total income (AMT_INCOME_TOTAL)?
  3. Does family status (NAME_FAMILY_STATUS) affect total income (AMT_INCOME_TOTAL)?
  4. Which gender (CODE_GENDER) is more likely to own a car (FLAG_OWN_CAR)?
  5. Is there a relationship between income type (NAME_INCOME_TYPE) and housing type (NAME_HOUSING_TYPE)?
  6. What is the relationship between age (DAYS_BIRTH) and total income (AMT_INCOME_TOTAL)?

This dataset seems to be quite a bit of work, so I should probably find things to talk about. Regardless, the project should revolve around the variable AMT_INCOME_TOTAL.

In general, people with academic degrees tend to have the most total income; and the less educated one is, the less total income one has. Furthermore, at any educational level, men generally make more than women, and the discrepency grows as educational level increases.

In [22]:

Note that the more negative DAYS_BIRTH is, the older the people are. Most people cannot get past $2 000 000$ dollars in income, which sort of makes sense. I find it interesting how the outliers who make more than $2 000 000$ dollars are mostly male.

Predictive Models¶

As it stands, the dataset looks rather horrible, but we will proceed with traning, testing, and fitting models. We shall see what will happen.

Splitting Data¶

predictors = dummyRecords.drop("AMT_INCOME_TOTAL", axis=1)
outcomes = dummyRecords[["AMT_INCOME_TOTAL"]]
xTrain, xTest, yTrain, yTest = model_selection.train_test_split(predictors, outcomes, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 200)

LASSO¶

In [39]:
appRecsLASSO = linear_model.Lasso(alpha=11100).fit(xTrain, yTrain)
yPredLASSOTest = appRecsLASSO.predict(xTest)
yPredLASSOTrain = appRecsLASSO.predict(xTrain)
print(metrics.r2_score(yTest, yPredLASSOTest))
print(metrics.r2_score(yTrain, yPredLASSOTrain))
print(metrics.root_mean_squared_error(yTest, yPredLASSOTest))
print(metrics.root_mean_squared_error(yTrain, yPredLASSOTrain))
